\contentsline {figure}{\numberline {5.1}{\ignorespaces (a) $d\mathcal {N}\tmspace -\thinmuskip {.1667em}/dz$ and (b) $d\mathcal {N}\tmspace -\thinmuskip {.1667em}/dX$ as a function of redshift for different minimum equivalent width thresholds, $W_{r,\mathrm {min}}^{\lambda 2796}$. Colors represent different $W_{r,\mathrm {min}}^{\lambda 2796}$. The black dotted lines are fits to the distribution of the functional form $f(z) = \frac {c}{H_o} n_0\tmspace +\thinmuskip {.1667em}\sigma _0\tmspace +\thinmuskip {.1667em}(1 + z)^{\epsilon }$, with the best fit $\epsilon $ value labelled. We see increasing values of $\epsilon $ with increasing equivalent width, driven by an enhancement of stronger ${\hbox {{\rm Mg}\kern 0.1em{\sc ii}}}$ absorbers around redshift 2 compared to lower redshifts. Vertical error bars represent $1\sigma $ uncertainties in each bin.\relax }}{23}
\contentsline {figure}{\numberline {5.2}{\ignorespaces (a) The comoving number density of absorbers multiplied by the absorbing cross-section, derived by fitting Equation\nobreakspace {}6.1\hbox {} to $d\mathcal {N}\tmspace -\thinmuskip {.1667em}/dX$, as a function of $W_{r,\mathrm {min}}^{\lambda 2796}$ with shaded $1\sigma $ uncertainties. As we examine samples with increasing minimum ${\hbox {{\rm Mg}\kern 0.1em{\sc ii}}}$ equivalent width thresholds, either the space density of absorbing cloud structures decreases, the absorbing cross-section decreases, or both parameters decrease. (b) The redshift evolution parameter, $\epsilon $, as a function of $W_{r,\mathrm {min}}^{\lambda 2796}$. Weak ${\hbox {{\rm Mg}\kern 0.1em{\sc ii}}}$ absorbers are more abundant at low redshift, leading to a negative coefficient $\epsilon $. Absorbers with equivalent widths near $0.3$\nobreakspace {}{\r A} do not evolve, with $\epsilon \simeq 0$. Strong ${\hbox {{\rm Mg}\kern 0.1em{\sc ii}}}$ absorbers evolve away at low redshift, showing a large positive $\epsilon $ increasing towards $z \sim 2$.\relax }}{25}
\contentsline {figure}{\numberline {5.3}{\ignorespaces (a) The equivalent width distribution of ${\hbox {{\rm Mg}\kern 0.1em{\sc ii}}}$ absorbers, defined as the redshift path density ($d\mathcal {N}\tmspace -\thinmuskip {.1667em}/dz$) in each equivalent width bin divided by the bin width. (b) The equivalent width distribution, defined as the comoving line density ($d\mathcal {N}\tmspace -\thinmuskip {.1667em}/dX$) in each equivalent width bin divided by the bin width. Error bars represent $1\sigma $ uncertainties in each bin. We fit each distribution with a Schechter function, capturing the self-similar power-law behavior of weak ${\hbox {{\rm Mg}\kern 0.1em{\sc ii}}}$ absorbers and the exponential power-law cutoff when observing the strongest ${\hbox {{\rm Mg}\kern 0.1em{\sc ii}}}$ systems.\relax }}{27}
\contentsline {figure}{\numberline {5.4}{\ignorespaces (a) The column density distribution of ${\hbox {{\rm Mg}\kern 0.1em{\sc ii}}}$ absorbers, defined as the redshift path density ($d\mathcal {N}\tmspace -\thinmuskip {.1667em}/dz$) in each column density bin dividided by the bin width. (b) The comoving line density ($d\mathcal {N}\tmspace -\thinmuskip {.1667em}/dX$) in each column density bin divided by the bin width. We fit this distribution with a Schechter function to accurately parameterize the low column density power-law slope and the exponential cutoff and high column densities.\relax }}{29}
\contentsline {figure}{\numberline {5.5}{\ignorespaces $\Omega _{\hbox {\relax \fontsize {8}{9.5}\selectfont {\hbox {{\rm Mg}\kern 0.1em{\sc ii}}}}}$ as a function of redshift. The cosmic mass density of ${\hbox {{\rm Mg}\kern 0.1em{\sc ii}}}$ stays roughly flat near a value of $1 \times 10^{-8}$, with a 0.5 dex increase from $z \sim 0.5$ to $z \sim 2$.\relax }}{32}
\contentsline {figure}{\numberline {5.6}{\ignorespaces (a) The $W_r^{\lambda 2796} \ge 0.3$\nobreakspace {}{\r A} equivalent width frequency distribution for The Vulture Survey in black compared to the exponential fit of\nobreakspace {}\cite {Nestor2005}, shown as the orange dashed line, and an exponential fit to The Vulture Survey data in purple. The exponential fits are of the form shown in Equation\nobreakspace {}5.11\hbox {}. (b) The cumulative distribution of The Vulture Survey data and two comparative exponential fits. The P(K-S) value shown compares our survey's data to the fit from\nobreakspace {}\cite {Nestor2005}. \relax }}{33}
\contentsline {figure}{\numberline {5.7}{\ignorespaces (a) $d\mathcal {N}\tmspace -\thinmuskip {.1667em}/dz$ as a function of redshift for equivalent widths in the range $0.02 < W_{r}^{\lambda 2796} \le 0.3$\nobreakspace {}{\r A}. We also include the survey data point from $0 < z < 0.3$ of\nobreakspace {}\cite {Narayanan2005} as shown by the dashed histogram. (b) $d\mathcal {N}\tmspace -\thinmuskip {.1667em}/dX$ as a function of redshift for the same population. Error bars represent $1\sigma $ uncertainties as calculated in Equations\nobreakspace {}5.1\hbox {} and\nobreakspace {}5.3\hbox {}. The red solid lines represent the no-evolution expectation, normalized at $z = 0.9$ and $d\mathcal {N}\tmspace -\thinmuskip {.1667em}/dz = 1.74$, matching\nobreakspace {}\cite {Narayanan2007}. The red dot-dashed line in panel (b) represents a linear fit to the binned data of the form $d\mathcal {N}\tmspace -\thinmuskip {.1667em}/dX = -0.28^{(\pm 0.04)}z + 0.92^{(\pm 0.04)}$. By this construction, $d\mathcal {N}\tmspace -\thinmuskip {.1667em}/dX = 0$ at $z = 3.3$, implying we should detect no weak ${\hbox {{\rm Mg}\kern 0.1em{\sc ii}}}$ absorbers past this redshift. This equivalent width range comprises exclusively ``weak'' ${\hbox {{\rm Mg}\kern 0.1em{\sc ii}}}$ absorbers.\relax }}{49}
\contentsline {figure}{\numberline {5.8}{\ignorespaces The equivalent width distribution of all detected ${\hbox {{\rm Mg}\kern 0.1em{\sc ii}}}$ absorbers, defined as the redshift path density ($d\mathcal {N}\tmspace -\thinmuskip {.1667em}/dz$) in each equivalent width bin divided by the bin width. The cosmic distribution of absorbing ${\hbox {{\rm Mg}\kern 0.1em{\sc ii}}}$ is well fit by a Schechter function, with the parameters detailed in Equation\nobreakspace {}5.9\hbox {}.\relax }}{50}
